{"type":"assistant.message","data":{"messageId":"b1bd8da9-2d19-4df2-ae93-11bfc088d868","content":"Three distinct C# 13 breaking changes. Here's what fails and why:\n\n---\n\n**1. `Buffer.cs` — `[InlineArray]` on `record struct` is now prohibited**\n\nC# 13 disallows `[InlineArray]` on record structs because the synthesized members (`Equals`, `GetHashCode`, `ToString`) are incompatible with inline array layout.\n\n**Fix:** Change `record struct` → `struct`:\n\n```csharp\n[System.Runtime.CompilerServices.InlineArray(10)]\nstruct Buffer\n{\n    private int _element0;\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n**2. `Generator.cs` — `stackalloc` in local function inside an iterator**\n\nC# 13 relaxed rules to allow `ref struct`/`unsafe` in iterators, but as a side effect, local functions are now analyzed *within* the iterator's context. `stackalloc` is still forbidden in iterators (the stack frame won't survive across `yield`), so this now errors.\n\n**Fix:** Extract to a separate static method:\n\n```csharp\nunsafe class DataGenerator\n{\n    IEnumerable<int> Generate()\n    {\n        yield return 1;\n        Process();\n    }\n\n    static void Process()\n    {\n        int* p = stackalloc int[10];\n        // ... work with pointer\n    }\n}\n```\n\n---\n\n**3. `Resolver.cs` — Ambiguous overload with `[]` collection expression**\n\nC# 13 introduces first-class implicit span conversions. Now `[]` is equally convertible to both `ReadOnlySpan<int>` and `Span<object>`, making the call ambiguous (in C# 12 only one conversion was applicable).\n\n**Fix:** Disambiguate with an explicit type:\n\n```csharp\nstatic void Main()\n{\n    Process(ReadOnlySpan<int>.Empty);\n    // or: Process((ReadOnlySpan<int>)[]);\n}\n```","toolRequests":[],"interactionId":"ee6dcc8d-ea0a-41d0-91ae-897eccd03b4b","reasoningOpaque":"","reasoningText":"The user is asking about specific C# 13 / .NET 9 breaking changes. Let me analyze each case:\n\n1. **Buffer.cs** - `InlineArray` on a `record struct`: C# 13 disallows `[InlineArray]` on `record struct` types. The fix is to change it to a plain `struct`.\n\n2. **Generator.cs** - `stackalloc` in iterators/async methods via local functions: C# 13 changed the rules. Actually, let me think... In C# 12, `stackalloc` was allowed in local functions inside iterators because the local function wasn't itself an iterator. \n\nIn C# 13, the compiler now treats local functions inside iterators as part of the iterator's scope for validation purposes, so `stackalloc` is no longer permitted even within those nested functions. The workaround would be to either move the stack allocation outside the iterator or switch to heap-allocated arrays instead. So the real issue is that local functions in iterators are now compiled as part of the state machine in C# 13, which means `stackalloc` isn't allowed since the stack frame persists across yield points—the fix is to extract it as a separate method or use a regular array with `Span<T>`. For the overload resolution problem, the collection expression `[]` is now convertible to both `ReadOnlySpan<int>` and `Span<object>` in C# 13, whereas the resolution rules in C# 12 would have preferred one over the other, creating an ambiguity that needs to be resolved by explicitly casting or choosing a specific overload.","outputTokens":2103},"id":"9ecc4927-ef92-4120-8707-86e604eb56e2","timestamp":"2026-04-08T01:11:07.446Z","parentId":"9a270572-023c-428a-b9d5-8e657b6164b1"}
